I feel like this observation is colored by Skallas living in a large city and then traveling the world. In a small town storylines always come back into your life and the characters missing now will reappear sooner or later. In a Twin Peaks type town you do get closure one day.

If you live in small town, you will meet the people from your high school again. You do not get the anonymity unless you physically leave town forever. If there is a storyline with an open ending from a decade ago you thought was over, it will return to you (for better or worse).

Good lore from Fr. Stephen de Young's lectures (The Whole Counsel of God) on Genesis is that the dove was seen as a "stupid" bird by ancient Jews. So on Noah's ark the dove bringing the olive branch meant it was guided by God. Other flood narratives had the smart raven find land.

Was thinking there's some beautiful Christian symbolism in Yu-Gi-Oh in how Yugi's favorite card Kuriboh means "cherub" and it's this angelic creature that sacrifices itself to protect him from harm, but apparently the name comes from "chestnut" and is based on Super Mario goombas

Come on it's literally this noble winged animal-like creature that sounds just like the Akkadian word "kuribu" for cherubs how the hell does it actually mean "Chestnut guy" in Japanese. Like it's pretty cherub-y on paper.

Underrated how in Sherlock Holmes the official lore is that Sherlock has an older brother named "Mycroft Holmes" who's an even bigger genius than him and literally runs the British Deep State by acting as an intermediary between all government departments and agencies.

In a story set in 1914 it's stated that Sherlock is 60 years old and Mycroft is 7 years older than him so his birth is supposedly ~1847. It doesn't quite work out but I wonder if this is yet another reference about 1948/1984 as those numbers keep popping up in British literature.
